We define an affine scheme to be a ringed space that is isomorphic to some \operatorname {Spec} (A), and a prescheme to be a locally-affine ringed space, i.e. such that every point has an open neighbourhood that is an affine scheme for the induced structure.
We define, in an evident way, morphisms of preschemes;
locally, they correspond to ring homomorphisms.

Let A be a complete local Noetherian ring, with residue field k, and let \mathfrak {X} be a proper formal scheme over A (endowed with its \mathfrak {r}(A)-adic topology). We suppose that
the local rings of \mathcal {O} _{ \mathfrak {X}} are flat A-modules, or, equivalently, that, if we endow \mathcal {O} _{ \mathfrak {X}} and A with the filtration given by powers of the maximal ideal of A, then the associated graded algebras satisfy \operatorname {gr} ( \mathcal {O} _{ \mathfrak {X}}) \simeq \operatorname {gr} ^0( \mathcal {O} _{ \mathfrak {X}}) \otimes _k \operatorname {gr} (A);
\operatorname {H} ^2( \mathfrak {X}_0, \mathcal {O} _{ \mathfrak {X}_0})=0, where we consider \mathfrak {X}_0= \mathfrak {X} \otimes _Ak as an algebraic scheme over k;
\mathfrak {X}_0 is projective.
Then, under these conditions, \mathfrak {X} is algebraisable, and, more precisely, is isomorphic to \overline {X}, where X is some projective A-scheme.

To show that f' is a local isomorphism at x, we note that f' induces an isomorphism \mathcal {O} _{y'} \to \mathcal {O} _x, as we see thanks to f'( \mathcal {O} _X)= \mathcal {O} _{Y'};
we also note that the (f')^{-1}(V) give a fundamental system of neighbourhoods of x when V runs over a fundamental system of neighbourhoods of y' (since f' is a closed map whose fibre at y' consists of the single point x).
We thus immediately deduce the following result, due to Chevalley in the "geometric" case:

Let f be a flat proper morphism, \mathscr { F } and \mathscr { G } locally free coherent sheaves on X, and y \in  Y;
suppose that \operatorname {H} ^1(X_y, \mathscr {H} \kern  -2.5pt \mathit {om} _{ \mathcal {O} _X}( \mathscr { F } _y, \mathscr { G } ))=0.
Then every homomorphism u_0 \colon \mathscr { F } _y \to \mathscr { G } _y is induced by a homomorphism u \colon \mathscr { F } |V \to \mathscr { G } |V, where V=f^{-1}(U) is the inverse image of a neighbourhood U of y.

Let u be an automorphism of X= \mathbb {P} (E).
Then there exists an invertible sheaf \mathscr { L } ' on Y, and an isomorphism v from E to E \otimes \mathscr { L } ' such that u is the isomorphism corresponding to \mathbb {P} (E) \xrightarrow { \sim } \mathbb {P} (E \otimes \mathscr { L } ')= \mathbb {P} (E);
the pair (v, \mathscr { L } ') is determined up to isomorphism.

Let X_0 be a scheme of finite type over the field k, and suppose that X_0 is simple (by which we mean absolutely simple) over k, but not necessarily proper over k.
Let A be a local Artinian ring with residue field k.
We are interested in finding schemes X that are flat over A, and such that X \otimes _A k=X_0 (this is the starting point of the "_theory of modules_", or of "structure variations" of X_0).

It is equivalent to give either such an X or, on the topological space X_0, a sheaf \mathcal {O} _X endowed with the following structures:






    \mathcal {O} _X is a sheaf of A-algebras;





    \mathcal {O} _X is endowed with an augmentation homomorphism \mathcal {O} _X \to \mathcal {O} _{X_0} (that is compatible with the A-algebra structures);





and with the above data being subject to the following conditions: the augmentation induces an isomorphism \mathcal {O} _X \otimes _A k \xrightarrow { \sim } \mathcal {O} _{X_0};
\mathcal {O} _X is flat over A, i.e. the graded algebra associated to \mathcal {O} _X filtered by the powers of the maximal ideal \mathfrak {m} of A is isomorphic to \operatorname {gr} ^0( \mathcal {O} _X) \otimes _k \operatorname {gr} (A), i.e. we have isomorphisms \mathfrak {m}^n \mathcal {O} _X/ \mathfrak {m}^{n+1} \mathcal {O} _X =  \mathcal {O} _{X_0} \otimes _k( \mathfrak {m}^n/ \mathfrak {m}^{n+1}).
The fundamental fact is the following:

Also, if we can find one X that is flat over A and that lifts X_0, then, by , the set of classes (up to isomorphism) of flat A-schemes that lift X_0 can be identified with \operatorname {H} ^1(X_0, \mathscr {A} \kern  -1.75pt \mathit {ut} (X)), where \mathscr {A} \kern  -1.75pt \mathit {ut} (X) denotes the sheaf of germs of automorphisms of the sheaf \mathscr { O_X } of A-algebras that are compatible with the augmentation.
The filtration of \mathcal {O} _X defines a filtration of \mathscr {A} \kern  -1.75pt \mathit {ut} (X), with the quotient of this sheaf by the n-th subgroup of the filtration being \mathscr {A} \kern  -1.75pt \mathit {ut} (X_n);
the graded algebra associated to this filtration is commutative, and can be identified with \mathfrak {G}_{X_0/k} \otimes _k \operatorname {gr} (A).
In particular, if \mathfrak {m}^{n+1} is the first power of \mathfrak {m} that is not zero, then F^n( \mathscr {A} \kern  -1.75pt \mathit {ut} (X)) (the last stage of the filtration) is in the centre of \mathscr {A} \kern  -1.75pt \mathit {ut} (X), and is isomorphic to \mathfrak {G}_{X_0/k} \otimes _k \mathfrak {m}^n;
it is also the sheaf of germs of automorphisms of X that induce the identity on X_{n-1}=X \otimes _A A/ \mathfrak {m}^n.
Using these results, we immediately obtain the following statements:

As we have already pointed out, it is not true in general that the formal scheme \mathfrak {X} over \mathcal {O} is algebraisable;
but we know that this is true, however, when X_0 is projective and H^2(X_0, \mathcal {O} _{X_0})=0 (), such as when X_0 is of dimension 1.
This is what gives some hope of constructing a scheme of modules over the integers for curves of a given genus...

